[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------|-------------------|--------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Scheduling Analyst | proposed -> under_review | Cognito group: `scheduling-analysts` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Governance Committee Member | under_review -> approved, under_review -> rejected | Cognito group: `surgical-governance` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | System (automated) | approved -> active (on effective date) | EventBridge scheduled rule with IAM role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Administrator | any -> superseded (emergency override) | Cognito group: `scheduling-admins` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **DynamoDB state tracking.** The schedule state table stores every transition:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DynamoDB Table: schedule_approvals
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   Partition Key: schedule_id (e.g., "2026-Q3-proposed-v2")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   Sort Key: transition_timestamp (ISO 8601)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   Attributes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     from_state: previous state
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     to_state: new state
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     actor_identity: Cognito sub or IAM principal ARN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     actor_name: human-readable name (for display, not for authz)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     reason: free-text justification (required for rejections)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     metadata: additional context (committee vote count, conditions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The current state of any schedule is the `to_state` of the most recent transition record. Query with `ScanIndexForward: false, Limit: 1` on the sort key to get the latest state in a single read.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **CloudTrail integration.** Every API Gateway call to the approval endpoints is logged in CloudTrail. This provides a tamper-resistant audit trail independent of DynamoDB. When a service chief asks "who approved this schedule change and when?", you can answer from two independent sources.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Implementation notes:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The Cognito user pool should federate with your hospital's identity provider (Active Directory, Okta, PingFederate). Don't maintain a separate user database for scheduling governance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - API Gateway resource policy should restrict access to the VPC or corporate network. Schedule approvals should not be reachable from the public internet.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Consider requiring multi-party approval (2 of N governance committee members) for schedules that reduce any service's allocation by more than 20%. Implement via a `pending_approvals` counter in the state record.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  392, 441[0m:[39m[49m ## Expected Results
